Variable Descriptions:

  • survival - Survival (0 = No; 1 = Yes)
  • pclass - Passenger Class (1 = 1st; 2 = 2nd; 3 = 3rd)
  • name - Name
  • sex - Sex
  • age - Age
  • sibsp - Number of Siblings/Spouses Aboard
  • parch - Number of Parents/Children Aboard
  • ticket - Ticket Number
  • fare - Passenger Fare
  • cabin - Cabin
  • embarked - Port of Embarkation (C = Cherbourg; Q = Queenstown; S = Southampton)

Special Notes:

  • Pclass is a proxy for socio-economic status (SES) (1st ~ Upper; 2nd ~ Middle; 3rd ~ Lower)

  • Age is in Years; Fractional if Age less than One (1). If the Age is Estimated, it is in the form xx.5

  • With respect to the family relation variables (i.e.sibsp and parch) some relations were ignored. The following are the definitions used for sibsp and parch.

  • Sibling: Brother, Sister, Stepbrother, or Stepsister of Passenger Aboard Titanic
  • Spouse: Husband or Wife of Passenger Aboard Titanic (Mistresses and Fiances Ignored)
  • Parent: Mother or Father of Passenger Aboard Titanic

  • Child: Son, Daughter, Stepson, or Stepdaughter of Passenger Aboard Titanic

  • Other family relatives excluded from this study include cousins, nephews/nieces, aunts/uncles, and in-laws. Some children travelled only with a nanny, therefore parch=0 for them. As well, some travelled with very close friends or neighbors in a village, however, the definitions do not support such relations.

Reuse the multiple plot function that enables us to plot more than one ggplot
# Multiple plot function
#
# ggplot objects can be passed in ..., or to plotlist (as a list of ggplot objects)
# - cols:   Number of columns in layout
# - layout: A matrix specifying the layout. If present, 'cols' is ignored.
#
# If the layout is something like matrix(c(1,2,3,3), nrow=2, byrow=TRUE),
# then plot 1 will go in the upper left, 2 will go in the upper right, and
# 3 will go all the way across the bottom.
#
multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  library(grid)
  
  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)
  
  numPlots = length(plots)
  
  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                     ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }
  
  if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])
    
  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))
    
    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))
      
      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}

Logistic Regression

We start with logistic regression with multiple predictors since we can see from the correlation matrix and the plot that there are multiple variables that seem to have a correlation with the response variable Survived. Also, starting with the most basic algorithm gives us an idea about the statistical significance of the predictors.
We considered Pclass, Age, SibSp, Parch as the different predictors because they all have some correlation with the response variable. Although there appears to be a strong correlation between Fare and Survived as well, we do not consider it because Fare and Pclass have a high correlation. In fact, the higher the fare, the better the Pclass.
In order to understand whether these predictors are useful or not in our model, we use the summary() function. In the summary we look at the p-values given by Pr(>|z|). In order for the predictor to be statistically significant it needs to be less than the threshold of 0.05(alpha). Since this condition is satisfied by our predictors we can say that all the predictors that we considered are statistically significant.
#Create the model
glm_fit <- glm(Survived ~ Pclass +  Sex + Age + Fam + Title, data = final_training, family = binomial)

#Find the summary of the model
summary(glm_fit)

Use the predict function to predict the values of the variable Survived in the validation set. Once we predict the value we want to play around with the threshold of our probability. In this case, any prediction over 0.6 gets assigned 1 which means that the person survived whereas any prediction below 0.6 gets assigned 0.
#Predict whether the person survived or not by using the algorithm
final_validation$predicted <- predict(glm_fit, final_validation, type = "response")

#Assign 1 or 0 to the predictions that we made
final_validation$new[final_validation$predicted > 0.6] <- 1
final_validation$new[final_validation$predicted < 0.6] <- 0
Create a confusion matrix to find True Positive, True Negative, False Positive and False Negative. Also calculate the prediction accuracy of the classification

paste0("Prediction accuracy is: ", round(100*(1-misclassification), 2), "%", sep="")
## [1] "Prediction accuracy is: 84.27%"
We can add interaction variables to see if the prediction accuracy improves or not. When we use the summary function we can notice that the predictor SibSp has a p-value higher than our threshold which means that it is not statistically significant in this case. Regardless, we do not remove the predictor SibSp from the model because if we include an interaction in a model we should also include the main effects, even if the p-values associated with their coefficients are not not statistically significant
#Create the model with the interaction terms
glm_fit_int <- glm(Survived ~ Pclass +  Sex + Age + Pclass*Sex + Fam + Title + Pclass*Fam + Pclass*Title + Age*Title, data = final_training, family = binomial)

Classification Tree

#Create the model
class_tree <- tree(as.factor(Survived) ~ Pclass +  Sex + Age + Fam + Title, data = final_training)

#Find the summary of the model
summary(class_tree)
## 
## Classification tree:
## tree(formula = as.factor(Survived) ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + Fam + 
##     Title, data = final_training)
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] "Sex"    "Pclass" "Fam"    "Age"   
## Number of terminal nodes:  7

## Misclassification error rate: 0.1713 = 122 / 712
Plot the classification tree with the different nodes indicated by the predictors mentioned in the tree model
#Plot the tree
plot(class_tree)
text(class_tree, pretty = 0)

By setting type as class we are telling the predict function that we want to classify the validation set that we pass as the new unknown data. The threshold for our classification is 0.5 such that any prediction that is over 0.5 will be classified as survived and anything equal to or below 0.5 will indicate death
#Predict whether the person survived or not by using the algorithm
final_validation$predtree <- predict(class_tree, final_validation, type = "class")

#Assign 1 or 0 to the predictions that we made
final_validation$newtree[as.integer(final_validation$predtree) > 0.5] <- 1
final_validation$newtree[as.integer(final_validation$predtree) <= 0.5] <- 0
#Create a confusion matrix
conf_tab_tree <- table(final_validation$predtree, final_validation$Survived)
conf_tab_tree
##    
##       0   1
##   0 100  19
##   1  11  48
#Calculate the misclassification error
misclassification_tree <- (conf_tab_tree[1,2] + conf_tab_tree[2,1])/(conf_tab_tree[1,1] + conf_tab_tree[1,2] + conf_tab_tree[2,1] + conf_tab_tree[2,2])

paste0("Prediction accuracy is: ", round(100*(1-misclassification_tree), 2), "%", sep="")
## [1] "Prediction accuracy is: 83.15%"
Check to see if pruning the tree will improve the prediction accuracy
#cv_trees <- cv.tree(class_tree, FUN = prune.misclass)

#Plot the pruned tree

text(prune_trees, pretty = 0)

#Predict whether the person survived or not by using the algorithm

#Create a confusion matrix

CForest

Here we use an implementation of random forest and bagging ensemble algorithm which is also known as conditional forest
#Add embarked here but make sure that the "" values are replaced to give only 3 factors
cf <- cforest(as.factor(Survived) ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + Fam + Fare + Title,
                 data = final_training, 
                 controls=cforest_unbiased(ntree=2000, mtry=3))
Once the model has been created we predict the value for a validation set that contains unknown data. Finally, we check the prediction accuracy for this latest model to check whether it predicts the survival better than our other models
